<item>
            <title>[SPARK-1235] DAGScheduler ignores exceptions thrown in handleTaskCompletion</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-1235</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;If an exception gets thrown in the handleTaskCompletion method, the method exits, but the exception is caught somewhere (not clear where) and the DAGScheduler keeps running.  Jobs hang as a result &amp;#8211; because not all of the task completion code gets run.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This was first reported by Brad Miller on the mailing list: &lt;a href=&quot;http://apache-spark-user-list.1001560.n3.nabble.com/Fwd-pyspark-crash-on-mesos-td2256.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://apache-spark-user-list.1001560.n3.nabble.com/Fwd-pyspark-crash-on-mesos-td2256.html&lt;/a&gt; and this behavior seems to have changed since 0.8 (when, based on Brad&apos;s description, it sounds like an exception in handleTaskCompletion would cause the DAGScheduler to crash), suggesting that this may be related to the Scala 2.10.3.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To reproduce this problem, add &quot;throw new Exception(&quot;foo&quot;)&quot; anywhere in handleTaskCompletion and run any job locally.  The job will hang and you can see the exception get printed in the logs.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
